d Thomas Carlyle. She shows how the attempt to write an alternative history brought historical writing into a close yet fraught relationship with literature. The result is a new account of that relationship as it took shape in the romantic period and as it continues to influence contemporary practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistorical fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aHistorical fiction, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 0aHistoricismxHistoryy19th century. 0aHistoriographyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aHistoriographyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and historyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aRomanticismzFrance. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Subjects & Themes / Historical Events .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172968340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729683/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK